  "prompt": "How can the universe be expanding faster than the speed of light?",
  "response": "The expansion of the universe can appear to exceed the speed of light due to a few key principles:\n\n1. Space itself is expanding\n- This isn't the same as objects moving through space\n- Space can stretch faster than light speed between distant points\n- No physical object is actually moving faster than light\n\n2. Cosmological expansion\n- Distant galaxies move away from each other due to universal expansion\n- The farther apart galaxies are, the faster they appear to recede\n- This is described by Hubble's Law\n\n3. Cosmic inflation theory\n- In the early universe, space expanded exponentially very rapidly\n- This expansion was faster than light speed\n- Doesn't violate special relativity because space itself is stretching\n\n4. No local speed limit violation\n- No single object is moving faster than light through space\n- The expansion happens to space itself, not within space\n\n5. Relativistic effects\n- Einstein's theories allow for space-time to behave differently at cosmic scales\n- Local physics rules don't always apply to universal dynamics\n\nThis phenomenon doesn't contradict physics because it's the fabric of space expanding, not matter moving through space faster than light.\n\nThe current understanding comes from observational cosmology and theoretical physics, particularly general relativity.",
